[test plan.it]
# gen108 (L13) — the bilingual ratchet (LOOP.md). The planner is symbolic over
# requires() facts, so the SAME topological sort serves Italian. Prerequisites
# arrive via "per X serve Y" (to do X you need Y) and the goal is asked with
# "come faccio ...?" / "come si fa ...?". The how-to phrasing is read from the
# ORIGINAL input (not the canonicalized surface), so "come si fa" survives the
# Italian function-word mapping. Same solver, same code path.

> per torta serve impasto
< Learned: requires(torta, impasto).
> per impasto serve uova
< Learned: requires(impasto, uova).
> per torta serve forno
< Learned: requires(torta, forno).
# uova before impasto (transitive), impasto and forno before torta. Derived.
> come faccio la torta?
< To make torta: uova, impasto, forno, then torta.
# A different Italian phrasing of the same request, through the same path.
> come si fa la torta?
< To make torta: uova, impasto, forno, then torta.
